{"seq": 15, "type": "message_added", "timestamp": "2026-05-03T07:09:34.583711+00:00", "data": {"message_type": "Agent", "content": "## Wipro Limited (WIPRO.NS) — Fundamental Research Report (as of 2026-04-30)\n\n### 1) Company profile & business context\n- **Company:** Wipro Limited  \n- **Sector / Industry:** Technology / Information Technology Services  \n- **What it is:** A large-cap IT services provider (software services, systems integration, consulting, and related technology services).  \n- **Market positioning (from fundamentals):** The market is valuing Wipro at a **moderate earnings multiple** and a **relatively high dividend yield**, suggesting investors are pricing in steadier cash generation rather than high-growth upside.\n\n---\n\n### 2) Market-based snapshot (valuation & shareholder return)\nFrom **get_fundamentals**:\n- **Market Cap:** ~**₹2.11T**\n- **P/E (TTM):** **~16.02**\n- **Forward P/E:** **~13.98** (implies earnings growth expectations vs current TTM)\n- **PEG:** **~1.36** (growth not extremely cheap, but not wildly expensive)\n- **Price / Book:** **~2.40**\n- **EPS (TTM):** **~₹12.56**\n- **Forward EPS:** **~₹14.40**\n- **Dividend Yield:** **~8.47%** (notable—large contributor to total return)\n- **Beta:** **~0.38** (lower volatility vs broader market)\n- **52-week range:** **₹186.5 – ₹273.1**\n- **Current trend references:**  \n  - **50-day avg:** ~₹198.66  \n  - **200-day avg:** ~₹235.20 (price below longer-term average based on these reference points)\n\n**Trader implication:** The combination of **mid-teens P/E + high dividend yield + lower beta** typically supports a “defensive value” profile. However, investors may also demand margin/cash-flow consistency because valuation doesn’t look “deeply distressed.”\n\n---\n\n### 3) Profitability & business performance (TTM indicators)\nFrom **get_fundamentals**:\n- **Revenue (TTM):** **~₹926.24B**\n- **Gross Profit:** **~₹235.07B**\n- **EBITDA:** **~₹176.50B**\n- **Net Income:** **~₹131.97B**\n- **Net Profit Margin:** **~14.25%**\n- **Operating Margin:** **~17.14%**\n- **ROE:** **~15.49%**\n- **ROA:** **~6.86%\n- **Free Cash Flow (FCF):** **~₹110.33B**\n\n**Trader implication:**  \n- Margins (gross/operating/net) and ROE are solid for a large IT services firm, and **FCF is meaningfully positive**, supporting the dividend.\n- If margins hold, **earnings visibility** likely improves—supportive for valuation stability.\n\n---\n\n### 4) Balance sheet strength & leverage\nFrom **get_fundamentals** and **get_balance_sheet (quarterly)**:\n\n**Key ratios / metrics (fundamentals):**\n- **Current Ratio:** **~2.05** (liquidity buffer)\n- **Debt to Equity:** **~22.85** (this figure appears very high—likely influenced by equity structure/book values; treat it as a signal to dig into composition rather than a single definitive “risk” number)\n- **Net Debt (balance sheet line item):** varies across quarters shown; one recent snapshot in fundamentals indicates **~₹44.15B** net debt.\n\n**Balance sheet trend highlights (quarterly series shown):**\n- **Stockholders Equity:** around **₹828B–₹897B** across the last several quarters provided.\n- **Total Assets:** **~₹1.29T–₹1.41T** (notable growth into the latest quarter shown).\n- **Working Capital:** **~₹428B–₹492B** (healthy operational liquidity).\n- **Goodwill & intangibles:** **very large** (goodwill ~**₹324B–₹368B** range in shown quarters), which is typical for acquirer-led growth history but should keep investors attentive to **impairment risk** and **integration discipline**.\n\n**Trader implication:** Liquidity and working capital appear supportive. The biggest thing to monitor is whether operating cash flows consistently cover obligations and maintain net cash/debt stability.\n\n---\n\n### 5) Cash flow quality (quarterly evidence) + shareholder cash return\nFrom **get_cashflow (quarterly)** (latest quarters in the dataset):\n\n**Operating cash flow:**\n- **Operating Cash Flow:**  \n  - 2025-03-31: **~₹49.31B**  \n  - 2025-06-30: **~₹37.47B**  \n  - 2025-09-30: **~₹33.87B**  \n  - 2025-12-31: **~₹42.59B**\n\n**Free Cash Flow (FCF):**\n- 2024-12-31: **~₹46.47B**\n- 2025-03-31: **~₹30.59B**\n- 2025-06-30: **~₹38.38B**\n- 2025-09-30: **~₹30.50B**\n- 2025-12-31: **~₹37.93B**\n\n**Investing & financing:**\n- **Capital Expenditure (quarterly):** roughly **-₹2.7B to -₹6.9B** (moderate relative to operating cash generation)\n- **Dividends paid:** appears **zero in some quarters** and **large outflows in others** (e.g., a large dividend outflow shown around 2024-09-30 / 2025-09-30 entries in the dataset).\n- **Financing cash flow** fluctuates due to **debt issuance/repayment**.\n\n**Trader implication:**  \n- Operating cash flow remains consistently positive—this is important for underwriting dividends and buybacks (if any).  \n- Volatility in FCF across quarters likely tracks working-capital movements and timing of cash conversion—not necessarily structural deterioration.\n\n---\n\n### 6) Income statement trend (quarterly evidence)\nFrom **get_income_statement (quarterly)** (latest quarters included):\n\n**Revenue (Total Revenue):**\n- 2025-03-31: **~₹223.19B**\n- 2025-06-30: **~₹225.04B**\n- 2025-09-30: **~₹221.35B**\n- 2025-12-31: **~₹226.97B**\n- 2026-03-31: **~₹235.56B** (latest shown)\n\n**Gross profit:**\n- Ranges **~₹64.10B to ~₹69.52B** (latest shown: **~₹68.36B**)\n\n**Operating income:**\n- Ranges **~₹35.54B to ~₹38.31B** (latest shown: **~₹34.95B**)\n\n**Net income:**\n- 2025-03-31: **~₹33.54B**\n- 2025-06-30: **~₹35.70B**\n- 2025-09-30: **~₹32.46B**\n- 2025-12-31: **~₹31.19B**\n- 2026-03-31 (latest shown): **~₹31.19B**? (dataset’s first row shows 2026-03-31 values; net income line indicates **~₹31.19B** for the latest quarter shown)\n\n**What changed recently (important):**\n- Revenue increased in the latest quarter (**~₹223B → ~₹235B**), but **operating income/net income did not rise proportionally** in the latest shown period—suggesting **cost pressures, mix shift, or one-offs**.\n- The dataset includes **“Unusual items”** and shows some variation in tax effect and other lines.\n\n**Trader implication:**  \n- Traders should not assume “revenue up = profit up.” For IT services, **margin discipline and utilization** matter.  \n- Watch next results for whether the latest quarter’s profitability weakness normalizes.\n\n---\n\n## Actionable insights for traders\n\n### A) Bull case drivers (fundamental)\n1. **Dividend support (high yield ~8.47%)** + consistent **positive operating cash flow** → can support downside and attract yield-focused capital.\n2. **Forward P/E lower than TTM P/E** (13.98 vs 16.02) → suggests earnings expectations may improve.\n3. **Healthy liquidity** (current ratio ~2.05) + meaningful FCF generation.\n\n### B) Bear case / risks\n1. **Profitability not tracking revenue cleanly** in the latest quarter shown (revenue up, but operating income/net income not increasing similarly).\n2. **Leverage metric (Debt/Equity very high)**—even if partly accounting-driven, rising effective debt or weaker cash conversion would be a watch-item.\n3. **Goodwill/intangibles are large**, so any future impairment or margin deterioration could weigh on equity metrics.\n\n### C) Practical “watchlist” signals for the next week/month\n- **Operating margin trend**: Are operating margins stabilizing around ~16–17% or compressing?\n- **Cash conversion**: Check whether **FCF stays closer to ~₹35–₹45B/quarter** rather than drifting lower.\n- **Working capital moves**: Large swings in receivables/payables can distort cash flow; consistent cash conversion is the key.\n\n---\n\n## Key points summary table\n\n| Category | Metric / Evidence | Latest / Notable Value(s) | Trader Takeaway |\n|---|---|---:|---|\n| Valuation | P/E (TTM) | ~16.02 | Reasonable valuation; not “deep value” but not expensive |\n| Valuation | Forward P/E | ~13.98 | Market expects improvement in earnings |\n| Shareholder return | Dividend yield | ~8.47% | High yield can cushion downside |\n| Growth proxy | PEG | ~1.36 | Moderate growth expectations |\n| Profitability | Net margin | ~14.25% | Solid margins for IT services |\n| Profitability | Operating margin | ~17.14% | Core profitability appears stable historically |\n| Returns | ROE | ~15.49% | Efficient capital generation |\n| Cash flow | FCF (TTM) | ~₹110.33B | Strong cash engine supports dividends |\n| Liquidity | Current ratio | ~2.05 | Healthy short-term liquidity |\n| Earnings trend | Revenue (quarterly) | Latest shown ~₹235.56B | Revenue growth—monitor if profit follows |\n| Earnings trend | Operating income (quarterly) | Latest shown ~₹34.95B | Margin may have softened recently |\n| Risk flag | Goodwill/intangibles | Very large base | Monitor impairment/discipline and margin sustainability |\n\nIf you want, I can also convert these fundamentals into a **simple bull/base/bear scenario** (with specific triggers like “operating margin threshold” and “FCF trend”) for short-term trade planning."}}
